@MrMino the Github "uses" feature to go over various repositories, looking at large companies that use the software, as well as knowing that I've broken peoples software in the past because of changes which bumped the version number (the projects I work on don't use SemVer) removing features that have been deprecated for several versions and thus were already returning warnings.

Second, version pinning in `setup.py` is generally not recommended, so when you go down into the dependency tree it is likely that you will find a pin that is `>=` and doesn't pin the upper version, so that the package can make sure that its dependency meets a certain requirement (or has a certain API) but doesn't limit any potential for a newer version.

I've even been bit by this myself in various projects where a dependency of a dependency didn't correctly pin, and my top-level project didn't version lock.
